c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.01a096fb-49db-4031-a8c1-555228abbe2e.prompt=Port for local end of tunnel\: c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.0e3052ce-08e4-44b8-88f1-9968fb636e4b.callout=SSH Shell Logoff should be in the error path of every step after connect to ensure the session is not left open. c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.2526d302-d063-42fe-8449-96ed42556270.callout=Open an ssh session to the remote host. c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.308dea32-a185-4e70-a358-42dfcc48bfd2.callout=This sample shows how to execute a command on a remote system using telnet, securely accross an ssh tunnel. c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.402445bb-6812-463a-84ba-45f0ed916976.description=
Closes a SSH Shell session created by SSH Shell Logon.  Must be in the same flow run context as the SSH Shell Logon operations that created the sessionId.

Inputs\:
sessionId - identifier of the ssh shell session to close.

Responses\:
success - the ssh shell session was closed successfully.
failure - something went wrong.  could not close the ssh shell session.
noaction - the ssh shell session could not be found.
c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.41e250eb-b651-4587-a2d0-c5f9aba6ddad.description=
Creates a SSH Shell session to be used by multiple SSH Shell operations.

Inputs\:
host - Hostname or ip address.
port - The port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input -in a syntax like host\:port-, if this exists.
username - Username to connect as.
password - Password of user. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.

Responses\:
success - SSH shell session and sessionId successfully created.
failure - An error occured while attempting to create the ssh shell session.

Extra Results\:
sessionId\: The ssh session identifier to be used for SSH Shell and SSH Shell Logoff operations.  This session identifier can only be used in the flow run context that it is created in.  multiple ssh shell sessions can be created and distinquished by assigning this sessionId to unique flow variables.
c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.431e9d85-9238-4f94-bbc1-a95994040190.prompt=Enter command\: c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.4d24e22e-f78d-4f6e-af04-d3b3adae904d.callout=Perform SSH Shell Logoff for success as well. c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.58955c00-c3de-42dc-a2a6-e0c4716cf189.prompt=Enter username\: c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.746977c0-dfd4-47a3-94e2-a8dc9fb11044.callout=Telnet to localhost (the RAS) port forwardLocalPort, and execute telnetComand. Note the sessionId result assigned from the input sessionId. See the Description for details. c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.74e7f491-d3cd-4f3d-8157-a11e29db51af.prompt=Enter password\: c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.7ff45a94-5d3b-4292-98ed-12d8bbdd9a15.prompt=Please enter a value\: c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.c05e4612-4c8e-416d-9397-e4394109be87.description=
Open a port forwarding tunnel between the RAS system and the remote ssh 
server. This will cause a local port to be opened for listening on the RAS server, 
and any connection made to the local port will be forwarded to the specified port 
on the remote host .


Inputs\:
sessionId - this is the sessionId, created by 'SSH Shell Logon', which the tunnel will be added to
forwardLocalPort - local port on the RAS to listen for connections on
forwardRemoteHost - any host or IP address which is reachable by the system on the other end of the tunnel
forwardRemotePort - the port on the remote host to send traffic to


NOTE\: This tunnel will stay open until the call to 'SSH Shell Logoff' is made to close the session. In the 
       event that something goes wrong, and the call is not made to 'SSH Shell Logoff', a suicide timer
       is started on the session when a tunnel is open. This timer will close the session, if it's still open,
       after the default RAS session timeout has expired. This ensures that ports are not left open 
       on the RAS, since there is no way to close the session interactively after the parent flow is gone.
c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.d44d751b-f80f-4aa4-aba2-13494563f28d.description=
Runs a command and allows user to specify that it runs locally (in this case no port should be specified), via ssh, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
host - Hostname or ip address.
port - Port number for connecting to the host.
username - Username to connect as.
password - Password of the user. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
protocol - The protocol used to run the command (can be one of ssh, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC, local, WMI, NASConnectTelnet, or HPOM).
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete; increase its value if you are getting incomplete output results or timeout.
command - The command to execute.
arguments - The arguments to pass to the command.
environment - Specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running command.
startDir - The path to the starting directory.
pty - Whether to use pty (used by ssh, GlobalShell. Valid values\: true, false).
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host. on RAS host (used by ssh, GlobalShell).
sasHost - The host we want to run the ROSH command on.
sasHostUsername - The username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost.
usernamePrompt - The prompt that when seen should send the username; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'NAS Login\:'
passwordPrompt - The prompt that when given should send the password; used by the Telnet protocol; when used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'Password\:'
outputPath - Network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems
nasDevice - The NAS device to run the command on when using the NASConnect protocol.
nasDeviceConsoleMode - The NAS device console mode used to run the command scripts that run the command on the given NAS device. If this input is empty, command scripts are not used, and the connection to the NAS device and the command are issued directly in the console; this is not recommended, since its error handling capabilities are limited and it might result in success even when the command fails to execute. The values for this input can be found in the NAS web interface, as a drop-down list when a new command script is created (ex. Cisco IOS enable).
hpomNode - Node on which the command is to be executed.
hpomProtocol - Protocol to communicate with HPOM (http or https).
characterSet - The characterSet name for stream encoding and decoding between the RAS and target machine. For example, SJIS,EUC-JP, UTF-8.  By default it is UTF-8 (used by ssh, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC).

Responses\:
success - The command was executed successfully.
failure - The command could not be executed.

Extra Results\:
stdErr - The STDERR of the command.
stdOut - The STDOUT of the command.

Notes\:
Telnet protocol - Since telnet is not a remote execution protocol but a shell protocol the response will always be successful if the command was executed in the remote shell.  The return code of the specified command cannot be determined in this protocol.  If you must use the telnet protocol with this operation besure to check the command results. Consider using ssh or rexec protocol instead.


c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.d999d2cd-af75-4e30-b9f5-3c6252f17a66.callout=Forward the local port, defined by flow input forwardLocalPort, to port 23 of the remote host.

c218fd2a-42ae-495d-b844-b8ea9dd59d69.description=
This flow demonstrates how to use an ssh tunnel to transport an insecure protocal, telnet in this case, accross a secure ssh tunnel. It does the following\:

Open an ssh session to a remote host
Open an ssh tunnel, which listens for connections on the local RAS, which forwards connections to port 23 on the remote host
Perform a telnet command against localhost\:forwardLocalPort
Close the ssh session

This is a rather rudimentary example, but it demonstrates the basics of using an ssh tunnel. 

Inputs\:
sshHost - Remote host to open the ssh connection to
username - username used to open the ssh session, and log in via telnet
password - password for the user
forwardLocalPort - local RAS port to listen on
timeout - timeout for both the ssh session and telnet command
usernamePrompt - usernamePrompt for the telnet session
passwordPrompt - passwordPrompt for the telnet session


Results\:
returnResult - the result of the telnet command

Responses\:
success - No errors were encountered during flow execution.
failure - Something went wrong.  Errors were encountered while executing this flow.


IMPORTANT NOTE\: Note the sessionId input added to the 'Telnet Command' step, and the result sessionId assigned from that input 
                It turns out that the flow variable sessionId collides with the flow's sessionId, and any step which is not one of the 
                'SSH Shell *' operations must use this mechanism to pass the ssh sessionId through to the next step, or it will be overwritten
                with an incorrect value, and the 'SSH Shell Logoff' step will fail. Alternatively you could store the sessionId returned from 
                'SSH Shell Logon' to a different flow variable, and assign the sessionId input for each 'SSH Shell *' operation from this new
                variable. Either way should work.
flow.name: SSH Shell Tunnel Example
